\section{Introduction}

The radiative transfer equation used for line-by-line (LBL) calculations
is

\begin{equation}\label{basic}
I_c = \int \text{d}\nu\, \phi_c(\nu)
      \int \text{d} z\, \Delta B(z,\nu) \tau(z,\nu)
 \approx \sum_{n=1}^{N_f} \phi_{nc} \Delta \nu_{nc}
               \sum_{i=1}^{N_p} \Delta B_{in} \tau^s_{in}
\end{equation}

where $\tau^s_{in}$ is the incremental transmittance due to strong
spectral lines.  Recall from wvs-024r2 that incremental transmittances
from strong and weak (pre-frequency-averaged or PFA) lines are combined
using

\begin{equation}\label{combined}
I_c \approx \sum_{n=1}^{N_f} \phi_{nc} \Delta \nu_{nc}
               \sum_{i=1}^{N_p} \Delta B_{ic} \tau^s_{in} \tau^w_{ic}\,.
\end{equation}

Memo wvs-026r2 developed a frequency-averaged incremental radiance in
each channel at each point along the path by exchanging the order of
summation in Equation (\ref{basic}) and then postponing the outer sum

\begin{equation}
\overline{I^s_{ic}} =
 \sum_{n=1}^{N_f} \phi_{nc} \Delta \nu_{nc} \Delta B_{in} \tau^s_{in}
 \approx
 \Delta B_{ic} \sum_{n=1}^{N_f} \phi_{nc} \Delta \nu_{nc}
  \tau^s_{in}\,.
\end{equation}

If there is no frequency averaging for LBL, this is simplified to

\begin{equation}
 \overline{I^s_{ic}} = \Delta B_{ic} \tau^s_{ic}\,.
\end{equation}

Exchanging the order of summation in Equation (\ref{combined}) we have

\begin{equation}\label{exchanged}
I_c \approx \sum_{i=1}^{N_p} \tau^w_{ic} \Delta B_{ic}
             \sum_{n=1}^{N_f} \phi_{nc} \Delta \nu_{nc} \tau^s_{in}
    = \sum_{i=1}^{N_p} \overline{I^s_{ic}} \tau^w_{ic}
\end{equation}

which is the same if there is no frequency averaging for LBL.  The
special treatment needed at the zero-thickness tangent-point layer is
applied when $\tau^s_{in}$ and $\tau^w_{ic}$ are calculated, so no
special care is needed here.

Memo wvs-026r2 developed the approximation 

\begin{equation}\label{deriv}
\frac{\partial I_c}{\partial x_k}
\approx \sum_{n=1}^{N_f} \phi_{nc} \Delta \nu_{nc} \sum_{i=1}^{N_p}
 \left(
  \frac{\partial \Delta B_{in}}{\partial x_k} -
  \Delta B_{in}
   \sum_{j=1}^i \frac{\partial \delta^s_{jn}}{\partial x_k}
  \right) \tau^s_{in}
 -
 \sum_{i=1}^{N_p} \overline{I^s_{ic}} \tau^w_{ic}
  \sum_{j=1}^i\frac{\partial \delta^w_{jc}}{\partial x_k}
\end{equation}

to combine LBL and PFA derivatives.

Setting aside frequency averaging in Equation (\ref{deriv}) and setting
$\frac{\partial \Delta B_{in}}{\partial x_k} \equiv 0$, the first term
becomes

\begin{equation}\label{final}
- \sum_{i=1}^{N_p} \Delta B_{in} \tau^s_{in}
  \sum_{j=1}^i \frac{\partial \delta^s_{jn}}{\partial x_k}\,.
\end{equation}

Special care must be taken for the zero-thickness tangent-point layer, both in
evaluating the inner sum here and the inner sum in the second term in Equation
(\ref{deriv}).  Subroutine {\tt dscrt\_dx} takes this special care in
evaluating Equation (\ref{final}).

By replacing $\Delta B_{in}$ by $\overline{I^s_{ic}}$ and $\frac{\partial
\delta^s_{jn}}{\partial x_k}$ by $\frac{\partial \delta^w_{jc}}{\partial
x_k}$, Equation (\ref{final}) becomes the second term in Equation
(\ref{deriv}).  Therefore, {\tt dscrt\_dx} can evaluate the second term
in Equation (\ref{deriv}).

In the PFA-only case, everything reduces to the LBL-only case, but without
frequency averaging:

\begin{equation}\begin{split}
I_c =\,& \int \text{d} z\, \Delta B(z,\nu) \tau(z,\nu)
 \approx \sum_{i=1}^{N_p} \Delta B_{ic} \tau^s_{ic}\\
\frac{\partial I_c}{\partial x_k}
 \approx\,& \sum_{i=1}^{N_p}
  \left(
   \frac{\partial \Delta B_{ic}}{\partial x_k} -
   \Delta B_{ic}
    \sum_{j=1}^i \frac{\partial \delta^w_{jn}}{\partial x_k}
   \right) \tau^w_{ic}
\end{split}\end{equation}

